# reorder.gbnf — MBOX-120 constrained-decoding grammar for `reorder` drafts.
#
# DESIGN — constrain the BONES, not the prose.
# Per arxiv 2603.03305 ("constrained decoding can degrade semantic quality
# when the grammar over-specifies the generated text"), this grammar only
# enforces the STRUCTURE of a reorder reply — the skeleton an operator's
# reorder confirmation always has — and leaves every word of the actual
# prose decoded FREELY by the model.
#
# Structure enforced (the "bones"):
#   1. a greeting line                  (free text, one line)
#   2. a free-form body                 (one-or-more sentences, NOT constrained)
#   3. a structured confirmation slot   (PO/order ref + ship-by date REQUIRED as
#                                         labelled tokens, but their VALUES are
#                                         free text — the model fills them,
#                                         including bracketed [confirm with
#                                         operator: ...] placeholders)
#   4. a signoff line                   (free text, one line)
#
# What is deliberately NOT constrained: word choice, sentence count in the
# body, tone, the literal values after the PO/ship-by labels. The grammar can
# refuse a reply that omits the confirmation slot entirely; it can NOT force a
# specific phrasing. That is the point — structure is cheap to enforce and
# safe; prose is where constrained decoding hurts, so we leave it alone.
#
# Default OFF behind CONSTRAINED_DECODING_ENABLED (see grammar-dispatch.ts).
# Only the llama.cpp local runtime consumes `grammar`; Ollama ignores it.

root      ::= greeting nl body nl confirm nl signoff

greeting  ::= line

# Body: one or more free-text lines (sentences/paragraphs). Word choice is
# entirely up to the model — this is just "at least one non-empty line".
body      ::= line (nl line)*

# Confirmation slot: both labels are required tokens, their values are free.
# The model supplies the order reference and the ship-by date (or a bracketed
# [confirm with operator: ...] placeholder when it does not know the fact).
confirm   ::= po-line nl ship-line
po-line   ::= ("PO" | "Order" | "Order ref" | "Reorder") ": " value
ship-line ::= ("Ship-by" | "Ship by" | "Shipping" | "Ships") ": " value

signoff   ::= line

# A line is one or more printable chars (no embedded newline). `value` is the
# same free-text token used after a structured label.
line      ::= char+
value     ::= char+
char      ::= [^\n]
nl        ::= "\n"
